Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient factory — singleton so connections are reused
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // Data service — singleton because it wraps HttpClient
        // and holds no per-user/per-page state
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient so each navigation creates a new instance
        // bound to its own ViewModel
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Avoids socket exhaustion from repeated instantiation. One instance reuses connections efficiently. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless API wrapper — safe to share. Depends on singleton `HttpClient`, so it must be singleton or transient (never scoped below its dependency). |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each page navigation should get a clean VM with fresh state. Prevents stale data leaking between navigations. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pairs with transient ViewModels — each navigation push creates a new page + VM pair. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that hold no mutable per-request state → **singleton**. UI-bound objects (pages, VMs) that carry screen state → **transient**. Use **scoped** only if you have a well-defined scope (MAUI doesn't create scopes per navigation by default, so scoped ≈ singleton in most MAUI apps — avoid it unless you manage scopes yourself).
